{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"da44e169-9e7d-4b67-9191-8c07d57e4fe1","content":"You can download `dotnet-trace` as a **standalone executable** — no SDK needed.\n\n**Inside the container, run:**\n\n```bash\ncurl -sSL https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-x64 -o /tmp/dotnet-trace\nchmod +x /tmp/dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**Then collect a CPU trace:**\n\n```bash\n# Find your app's PID\n/tmp/dotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect with the cpu-sampling profile\n/tmp/dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling -o /tmp/trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Key notes:**\n- For ARM64 containers, use `linux-arm64` instead of `linux-x64`.\n- The resulting `.nettrace` file can be analyzed with **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or converted to Speedscope format with `--format speedscope`.\n- To copy the trace out: `docker cp <container>:/tmp/trace.nettrace .`","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9beb993e-f2c2-4ada-9f85-57af1f0bd973","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to get `dotnet-trace` into a Linux container that doesn't have the .NET SDK installed, to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app experiencing high CPU.\n\nThis is a knowledge question about .NET diagnostics tooling. I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to search the codebase.\n\nKey points:\n1. `dotnet-trace` is a .NET global tool, but you can also get it as a standalone download (no SDK required).\n2. For containers without the SDK, you can download the standalone version directly.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":392,"requestId":"6414:984F8:143182A:17896AE:69EC155F"},"id":"17184b25-9182-43d9-a1e8-0c8aa70d24d6","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:14:17.121Z","parentId":"fb7e8803-8390-43ae-a2c6-d7c109862433"}
